message.content:
The start symbol S has only one production:

S → NT8 NT6

NT8 can generate
1. the single terminal t11 (via NT8 → 't11'), or  
2. strings obtained by repeatedly appending NT25 (= t4) to that t11 (via the recursive rule NT8 → NT8 NT25).

Consequently every string produced by NT8 must begin with the terminal t11 and never with any other token.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with t4, not with t11. Therefore no derivation starting from S can match the first symbol of the string, and S cannot generate the whole string.

Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol has a single production:

S → NT8 NT6

Therefore the string must split into a prefix generated by NT8 and a suffix generated by NT6.

Examination of the grammar shows that every derivation of NT8 ultimately uses the rule

NT8 → 't11'

(optionally followed by repetitions of NT25 → 't4' | 't5' via the recursive rule NT8 → NT8 NT25).  
Hence any string produced by NT8 must contain the terminal token t11.

The given string
t5 t24 t10 t10 t10 t5 t24 t24 t26 t9 t10 t13 t7 t15 t25 t15 t24 t13 t26
contains no occurrence of t11 at all.

Consequently NT8 cannot generate any substring of the provided string, so S cannot generate the string.

Answer: No

For the start symbol we must have  
S ⇒ NT8 NT6  

1. NT8 produces strings of the form t11 (t4 | t5)*  
   (base production NT8 → 't11', recursive NT8 → NT8 NT25 with NT25 → 't4'|'t5')  

2. NT6, in order to generate more than one token, must use  
   NT6 → NT22 NT28  
   (the only other productions give single terminals t23 or t26).

3. NT28 can produce only  
   • 't7'  
   • 't9'  
   • 't13 t30'  
   (from NT28 → 't7' | 't9' | NT2 NT46, with NT2 → 't13', NT46 → 't30').

Therefore the very last token(s) of any string derived from S must be one of
   t7   or   t9   or   t13 t30.

The given string ends with “… t18 t2”.  
None of the allowed endings for NT28 matches “t18 t2”, so no derivation is possible.

Hence the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

In every derivation the start symbol expands as  

S → NT8 NT6  

Hence the first terminal produced must come from NT8.  
The rules for NT8 are  

NT8 → NT8 NT25  
NT8 → 't11'  

Thus NT8 always produces the terminal 't11' as its left-most (and earliest) symbol; any further symbols it adds are generated afterwards by NT25, which can only be 't4' or 't5'. Consequently every string generated by the grammar must begin with the token t11.

The given string begins with t13, not t11:

t13 t23 t25 …

Since the first required token does not match, the string cannot be derived from the grammar.

No

The start–symbol expands only one way:

S → NT8 NT6

1.  NT8  
   NT8 can generate  
   – the single terminal  t11, or  
   – t11 followed by one or more t4 / t5 ‘s (because NT8 → NT8 NT25 and NT25 → t4 | t5).  

   In the given string the very first symbol is t11 and the next symbol is t23 (not t4 / t5), so the only
   possibility is

   NT8 ⇒ t11

   Hence every remaining token (positions 2–35) has to be produced by NT6.

2.  NT6  
   NT6 has the rules  

        NT6 → t23         |  t26          |  NT22 NT28  

   The tail of the string consists of 34 tokens, so NT6 must use the binary rule

        NT6 → NT22 NT28

3.  NT28  
   NT28 can generate  

        NT28 → t9   |  t7   |  NT2 NT46

   The last token of the whole string is t7, so NT28 must be the single terminal t7.
   Consequently NT22 has to cover the 33-token block from position 2 to 34.

4.  NT22  
   NT22 has only one rule:

        NT22 → NT14 NT4

   Therefore those 33 tokens must be split into

        NT14  (some prefix)   NT4  (the suffix that ends with position 34).

5.  NT14  
   The possibilities for NT14 are  

        NT14 → t23
        NT14 → NT19 NT34
        NT14 → NT51 NT8

   •  If NT14 were the single terminal t23 it would occupy exactly one token.  
      Then NT4 would have to generate the remaining 32-token suffix (positions 3–34).

   •  If NT14 → NT19 NT34, the rightmost symbol produced by NT19 must be t8  
      (because NT34 is the single terminal t2 and NT19 → NT35 NT9 with NT9 → t8).  
      Scanning the 32-token block (positions 2–33) we find every t8 is followed by
      t23 or t9, never by t2; the pattern “t8 t2” required by this rule is absent.  
      Hence this alternative is impossible.

   •  NT14 → NT51 NT8 would make the last token generated by NT14 a t11
      (since NT8 always starts with t11 and can only be followed by t4 / t5).
      Within positions 2–33 the only t11 is at position 20, and the symbol
      immediately after it is t30, which is not allowed after t11 in an NT8-string,
      so this alternative is also impossible.

   Thus the only remaining theoretic option is

        NT14 ⇒ t23   (occupying position 2)

6.  NT4  
   With NT14 fixed to position 2, NT4 must now generate the 32-token suffix
   from position 3 to 34.  NT4 can expand as

        NT4 → t30
        NT4 → NT16 NT39

   The first alternative is a single token and is therefore impossible.
   So NT4 must use NT16 NT39, i.e. those 32 tokens must be split once more:

        NT16  (prefix)   NT39  (suffix that ends at position 34)

   NT39 itself is NT1 NT50, where NT50 begins with t8 (NT50 → NT9 NT22, NT9 → t8).
   But in the suffix that ends with position 34 (… t25 t15 t8 t23 t2 t30) the first
   occurrence of t8 is not at the very start of that block, hence NT39 cannot match
   the required pattern.  Consequently NT4 cannot generate the needed 32-token
   sequence.

Because every possible expansion path for NT22 fails, NT6 (and therefore S) cannot
generate the given string.  Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only way the terminal t2 can be produced in this grammar is through the rule

NT14 → NT19 NT34 with NT34 → 't2'.

Hence every occurrence of t2 in a derivable string must be immediately preceded by the substring generated by NT19.  
The possible forms of NT19 are:

1. NT19 → 't23'     (generates one token t23)  
2. NT19 → 't24'     (generates one token t24)  
3. NT19 → NT35 NT9  
    with NT35 → 't10' | 't24' and NT9 → 't8'  
    (generates the two–token sequences t10 t8 or t24 t8)

Therefore every t2 in a legal string must be immediately preceded by
t23, t24, t10 t8, or t24 t8.

In the candidate string the first occurrence of t2 is

… t9 t8 t2 …

Here the token t2 is preceded by t8 and, before that, by t9.  
None of the four required patterns (t23, t24, t10 t8, t24 t8) appears
immediately before this t2, so this t2 cannot be produced by the grammar.
As this token cannot be derived, the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

Hence the given string is not in the language.  

No
